Lizzie's group, the Hilltown team, the Green Valley crew, the Riverbank squad, and the Meadowlane gang embarked on a mission to clean up some farmlands. The total area of the given farmlands spans 28,500.0 square feet. 

On the first day, Lizzie's group managed to clean an area of 3,534 2/3 square feet, while the Hilltown team covered 4,675 5/8 square feet, and the Green Valley crew cleaned an area of 2,847 7/9 square feet. 

On the second day, the Riverbank squad cleaned 6,301 1/3 square feet, and the Meadowlane gang cleaned an area of 3,467 4/5 square feet.

Given the collective effort of all the groups across two days, how many square feet of farmland remains to be cleaned up?

Lucas has 240 feet of fencing. He needs to enclose a rectangular space such that the area is fifteen times its perimeter. Assuming he uses up all his fencing material, how many feet is the largest side of the enclosure?

Madison studies in a school where the bell rings once a class starts and again when class gets over. There is a break of 15 minutes after every class. On Monday, Madison has some classes in order. Right now Madison is in his last class and the bell would have rung 9 times by now. How many classes does Madison have on Monday?

Malcolm has 240 followers on Instagram and some followers on Facebook. The number of followers he has on Twitter is half the number of followers he has on Instagram and Facebook combined. Meanwhile, the number of followers he has on TikTok is 3 times the number of followers he has on Twitter, and he has 510 more followers on Youtube than he has on TikTok. Malcolm has 3840 followers on all his social media. How many followers does Malcolm have on Facebook?
Marcella has 20 pairs of shoes. If she loses 9 individual shoes, what is the greatest number of matching pairs she could have left?

Marcus has two containers. The first container was $\frac{4}{5}$ full of juice, and the second container was empty. He poured all the juice from the first container into the second container, at which point the second container was $\frac{2}{3}$ full of juice. What is the ratio of the volume of the first container to the volume of the second container?
$\textbf{(A) } \frac{3}{4} \qquad \textbf{(B) } \frac{5}{6} \qquad \textbf{(C) } \frac{7}{8} \qquad \textbf{(D) } \frac{8}{9} \qquad \textbf{(E) } \frac{9}{10}$

Marcy keeps a certain amount of water by her desk. She takes a sip every five minutes, and each sip is 40 ml. It takes her 250 minutes to drink the whole bottle of water. How many liters of water does Marcy keep by her desk?
Maria needs 21 cartons of berries to make a berry cobbler. She already has 4 cartons of strawberries and 8 cartons of blueberries. How many more cartons of berries should Maria buy?

Marilyn has 40 bananas that must be put away in boxes. Daniel comes to help and brings some cookies to share with Marilyn. If there are 8 boxes and 5 bananas must go in each box, how many cookies did Daniel bring?
Mark has two numbers, $c$ and $d$. When he divides $c$ by 52, he gets a remainder of 48. When he divides $d$ by 87, he gets a remainder of 82. What is the remainder when he divides $c+d$ by 29?

Marlon had 30 female baby bunnies in his hutch. They matured after four months, and he gave 2/5 of them to his friend Rodney. After another three months the bunnies conceived and gave birth to a certain number of kittens each. Marlon now has a total of 54 bunnies in his hutch. How many kittens did each bunny give birth to?

Marnie makes bead bracelets. She bought 5 bags of 50 beads, 2 bags of 100 beads, 3 bags of 75 beads, and 4 bags of 125 beads. If 65 beads are used to make one bracelet, how many bracelets will Marnie be able to make out of the beads she bought?

Martians measure angles in tuvels, and there are $400$ tuvels in a full circle. Calculate how many tuvels there are in an acute angle measuring $45^\circ$.
$\text{(A)}\ 40 \qquad \text{(B)}\ 50 \qquad \text{(C)}\ 100 \qquad \text{(D)}\ 80 \qquad \text{(E)}\ 200$

Marty plans to paint a fence and can choose from five different colors: blue, green, yellow, black, or white. He can also choose from four different painting tools: a brush, a roller, a sponge, or a spray gun. How many different combinations of color and painting tool can Marty choose?

Matthew, the baker, usually takes some time to assemble ingredients, 1.5 hours to bake the cakes, and another 1 hour to decorate each cake with cinnamon sprinkles. One day, his oven failed to reach the correct temperature and it took twice as long for the cakes to bake as they usually take. On that day, it took Matthew 5 hours to make his famous caramel-apple coffee cakes. How long does it usually take for Matthew to assemble ingredients?

Max and Liz are among 30 students taking either German or Spanish. Both Max and Liz are the only students enrolled in both classes. Liz notes that there are exactly three times as many students in the German class as in the Spanish class. How many students are taking German but not Spanish?

Maxwell leaves his home and walks toward Brad's house at 4 km/h. One hour later, Brad leaves his home and runs toward Maxwell's house at a certain speed. The distance between their homes is 74 kilometers. The total time it takes Maxwell before he meets up with Brad is 8 hours. What is Brad's running speed?
Melissa scored 120.0 points in all her games total. If she played 10.0 games, how many points did she score in each game.

Meteorology enthusiast Kong Zongming observed over $x$ days (where $x$ is a positive integer) that: ① There were 7 rainy days; ② There were 5 afternoons that were sunny; ③ There were 6 mornings that were sunny; ④ When it rained in the afternoon, the morning was sunny. Then, $x$ equals ( )
A: 7
B: 8
C: 9
D: 10

Mia needs to add 58 and 46 and then round the result to the nearest hundred. Instead of adding first, she rounds each number before adding: she rounds 58 to 100 and 46 to 50, and concludes that the sum is $150$. What is the correct sum when rounded to the nearest hundred?

Michael writes down all the integers between 1 and \( N \) inclusive on a piece of paper and discovers that exactly \( 40\% \) of them have leftmost digit 1. Given that \( N > 2017 \), find the smallest possible value of \( N \).
Michelle began her pizza delivery route with 0.5 tank of gas in her car . When she made it back to the pizzeria , 0.17 tank of gas was left. Michelle used _____ gas .

Mike drives his new Corvette from San Francisco to Las Vegas, a journey of 640 miles. He drives the first half of the trip at an average rate of 80 miles per hour, but has to slow down for the second half of his journey. The second half of the trip takes him 200 percent longer than the first half. What is his average rate in miles per hour for the entire trip?
Mike picked 8 pears and Jason picked 7 pears from the pear tree. Fred picked 6 apples from the apple tree. Sarah picked 12 apples from the apple tree. How many pears and apples were picked in total?

Miki has a dozen oranges of the same size and a dozen pears of the same size. Miki extracts 12 ounces of pear juice from 4 pears and 6 ounces of orange juice from 3 oranges. She decides to make a pear-orange juice blend using 8 pears and 6 oranges. What percent of the blend is pear juice?
(A) 50%
(B) 60%
(C) 66.67%
(D) 70%
(E) 75%

Mona brought 20 cookies to share in class. Jasmine brought fewer cookies than Mona. Rachel brought 10 more cookies than Jasmine. Mona, Jasmine, and Rachel brought altogether 60 cookies to share in class. How many cookies did Jasmine bring?
Mork pays a tax rate of 45% on his income, while Mindy pays a certain tax rate on hers. If Mindy earned 4 times as much as Mork did, their combined tax rate was 25%. What is Mindy's tax rate?

Mr. Callen decided to diversify his business by investing in various artisanal items. He bought the following items to resell at a profit:

1. 18 paintings at $75 each
2. 25 wooden toys at $30 each
3. 12 handmade hats at $20 each
4. 10 leather wallets at $50 each
5. 35 ceramic mugs at $10 each

Due to shifting market demands, Mr. Callen ended up selling the items at lower prices than he intended. The selling prices and loss percentages were as follows:

1. Paintings: Sold for 22% less than the initial price
2. Wooden toys: Sold for 27% less than the initial price
3. Handmade hats: Sold for 15% less than the initial price
4. Leather wallets: Sold for 5% less than the initial price
5. Ceramic mugs: Sold for 12% less than the initial price

Calculate the total loss Mr. Callen made from the sale of these artisanal items.
Mr. Karan borrowed a certain amount at 6% per annum simple interest for 9 years. After 9 years, he returned Rs. 8410. Find out the amount that he borrowed.

Mr. N, aiming to maximize his profit, holds a patent for a unique product and can sell it only in countries A and B. The demand for his product in these countries is represented by the functions \( q_{A}=40-2P \) and \( q_{B}=26-P \), where \( q_{A} \) and \( q_{B} \) are the quantities of the product in countries A and B, respectively, and \( P \) is its price. Resales of Mr. N's product between the countries involve significant costs for his buyers, so Mr. N can set different prices for his product in each country. Regardless of the production country, the shipping cost to the other country is fixed at 1. Mr. N discovered that the production costs of his product do not depend on the production country and are described by the function \( TC(Q)=8Q+1 \). Mr. N can register his enterprise and produce the product in any of the countries, but they have different taxation systems. In country A, there is a proportional tax system with a fixed rate of 15%. In country B, there is a progressive multi-tier taxation system, with the rates indicated in the table:

| Profit | Up to 30 | From 30 to 100 | From 100 to 150 | Above 150 |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| Tax, % | Exempt | 10 | 20 | 30 |

What will Mr. N's profit be after taxes? What quantity of the product and at what price will be sold in each country?
Nancy has 7 black balloons. Mary has 4 times more black balloons than Nancy. Mary have _____ black balloons now .
Nellie started with 380 legos. She accidentally lost 15% of her legos during a move and later gave her sister 1/8 of the remaining legos. How many legos does Nellie have now?

Nine balls, numbered $1, 2, \cdots, 9$, are placed in a bag. These balls are identical except for their numbers. Person A draws a ball from the bag, which has the number $a$. After placing it back, person B draws another ball from the bag, which has the number $b$. The probability that the inequality $a - 2b + 10 > 0$ holds is
A. $\frac{52}{81}$
B. $\frac{59}{81}$
C. $\frac{60}{81}$
D. $\frac{61}{81}$

Ninety-nine children are standing in a circle, each initially holding a ball. Every minute, each child with a ball throws their ball to one of their two neighbors. If two balls end up with the same child, one of these balls is irrevocably lost. What is the minimum time required for the children to have only one ball left?

Number of integer solutions for the inequality \(x-1 < (x-1)^{2} < 3x + 7\):
(A) Equal to 4.
(B) Less than 4.
(C) Greater than 5.
(D) Equal to 5.
(Chinese Junior High Mathematics League, 1993)
On a 3x3 grid of evenly spaced points (each unit distance apart), how many different rectangles can be formed by using these points as vertices?

On a beautiful spring evening, Dupont and Durand were playing dice on a cafe terrace. They took turns rolling two dice. If the sum was 7, Durand won a point, and if the sum was 8, Dupont won a point. Whom would you bet on if you had to place a wager?

On a board, 'MATHEMATICS' is spelled out with 11 magnets, one for each letter. 'M', 'A', 'T', 'H', 'E', 'M', 'A', 'T', 'I', 'C', 'S' are the letters used. If three vowels and two consonants fall off and are put away in a bag, and considering that the 'A's and 'T's are indistinguishable, count the number of distinct possible collections of letters that could be put into the bag.

On a board, nine quadratic trinomials are written: \(x^{2}+a_{1} x+b_{1}, x^{2}+a_{2} x+b_{2}, \ldots, x^{2}+a_{9} x+b_{9}\). It is known that the sequences \(a_{1}, a_{2}, \ldots, a_{9}\) and \(b_{1}, b_{2}, \ldots, b_{9}\) are arithmetic progressions. It turns out that the sum of all nine trinomials has at least one root. What is the maximum number of the original trinomials that may not have any roots?

On a circle with a circumference of \(n\) (where \(n\) is a positive integer), the integers \(0, 1, \ldots, n-1\) are placed at equal distances in a clockwise direction. Each integer is colored either red or blue, with the condition that each color includes at least one non-zero integer. It is known that there exists a subset \(S \subsetneq \{0, 1, \ldots, n-1\}\) with \(|S| \geq 2\), which satisfies the following property: for any directed arc \((x, y)\) of length belonging to \(S\), with endpoints of different colors, the integer corresponding to the endpoint \(y\) is also in \(S\). Prove that there exists a non-trivial positive divisor \(d\) of \(n\) (i.e., \(d \notin \{1, n\}\)), such that if the length of the arc \((x, y)\) is divisible by \(d\) and \(d\) does not divide both \(x\) and \(y\), then \(x\) and \(y\) must be the same color.

On a circle, \( n > 1 \) points are marked, called positions, dividing it into equal arcs. The positions are numbered clockwise from 0 to \( n-1 \). Vasya places a token on one of these positions. The following actions, called moves, are repeated an unlimited number of times: Petya names a natural number, and Vasya moves the token clockwise or counterclockwise by the number of positions specified by Petya. If at any point after a move the token lands on position number 0, Vasya loses, and Petya wins. For which values of \( n \) can Petya always win, regardless of Vasya's moves?

On a drying rack, there are $n$ socks hanging in a random order (as they were taken out of the washing machine). Among them are two favorite socks of the Absent-minded Scientist. The socks are blocked by a drying sheet, so the Scientist cannot see them and picks one sock at a time by feel. Find the expected number of socks the Scientist will have removed by the time he has both of his favorite socks.

On a number line where the markings are equally spaced, what is the number $x$ if nine steps are taken to get from 0 to 36?
$\text{(A)}\ 20 \qquad \text{(B)}\ 24 \qquad \text{(C)}\ 28 \qquad \text{(D)}\ 32 \qquad \text{(E)}\ 36$

On a plane, a point \( O \) is marked. Is it possible to position on the plane: a) five circles; b) four circles, not covering point \( O \), such that any ray starting at point \( O \) intersects at least two circles? ("Intersects" means having a common point.)

On a sphere, two points \( A \) and \( B \) are fixed. Find the geometric locus of the third vertices \( C \) of spherical triangles \( A B C \) such that the quantity \( \angle A + \angle B - \angle C \) is constant.

On the ellipse $\frac {x^{2}}{4}+ \frac {y^{2}}{3}=1$, there is a moving point $P$. For the circle $E: (x-1)^{2}+y^{2}=1$, any line passing through the center of circle $E$ intersects the circle at points $A$ and $B$. For the circle $F: (x+1)^{2}+y^{2}=1$, any line passing through the center intersects the circle at points $C$ and $D$. The minimum value of $\overrightarrow{PA}\cdot \overrightarrow{PB}+ \overrightarrow{PC}\cdot \overrightarrow{PD}$ is \_\_\_\_\_\_.

On the sides \(AB, BC, CD,\) and \(DA\) of a spatial quadrilateral \(ABCD\) (or on their extensions), points \(K, L, M,\) and \(N\) are taken such that \(AN = AK, BK = BL, CL = CM,\) and \(DM = DN\). Prove that there exists a sphere tangent to the lines \(AB, BC, CD,\) and \(DA\).

Once a week, it takes Kitty 5 minutes to pick up toys and straighten the living room. It takes her some minutes to vacuum the living room floor, seating and drapes. She spends 15 minutes cleaning the windows and 10 minutes dusting the furniture. After 4 weeks, Kitty has spent 200 minutes cleaning just the living room. How long does it take Kitty to vacuum the living room floor, seating and drapes?

One hundred bricks, each measuring $3''\times11''\times20''$, are to be stacked to form a tower. Each brick can be oriented to contribute $3''$, $11''$, or $20''$ to the tower's height. How many different tower heights can be achieved using all one hundred bricks?
One more than the reciprocal of a certain number is $\frac{9}{4}$. What is this original number expressed as a common fraction?
One number exceeds another by 10. The larger number is 22. What is the sum of the two numbers?

One of the factors of $x^4 + 16$ is: 
- $\textbf{(A)}\ x^2 + 4$
- $\textbf{(B)}\ x+2$
- $\textbf{(C)}\ x^2-4x+4$
- $\textbf{(D)}\ x^2-8$
- $\textbf{(E)}\ \text{none of these}$
- **A.** $x^2 + 4$
- **B.** $x + 2$
- **C.** $x^2 - 4x + 4$
- **D.** $x^2 - 8$
- **E.** None of these

Our school's boys basketball team has 16 players, including a set of 4 quadruplets: Ben, Bryan, Bob, and Bill. In how many ways can we choose 5 starters if exactly three of the quadruplets are in the starting lineup?

Our school's girls volleyball team has 16 players, including a set of triplets (Missy, Lauren, and Liz) and a set of twins (Anna and Mia). In how many ways can we choose 7 starters if the restriction is that not all 3 triplets can be in the starting lineup and the twins cannot both be starters?

Out of all reporters for a certain wire service, 15% cover local politics in Country X, 10% cover local politics in Country Y, and 8% cover local politics in Country Z. On the other hand, 50% of reporters who cover politics for the wire service do not cover local politics in these three countries. Furthermore, 5% cover international politics, and 2% cover economics or other subjects. What percent of the reporters for the wire service do not cover politics at all, either local or international?

Oxford High School has 75 teachers, 1 principal, 3 vice principals, and 20 other staff members. There are 35 classes with each having different numbers of students ranging from 15 to 30. Calculate the total number of people in Oxford High School, considering that the average number of students per class is 23.
Paige had one hundred ten homework problems. She finished some of them but still had seven pages of problems to do. Each page has 9 problems on it. How many problems did Paige finish?

Parallelogram $ABCD$ has vertices $A(1,3)$, $B(3,8)$, $C(7, 6)$, and $D(5, 1)$. It is first reflected over the $y$-axis, producing parallelogram $A'B'C'D'$, and then $A'B'C'D'$ is reflected over the line $y = -x$ to form $A''B''C''D''$. What is the ordered pair of $D''$ in the coordinate plane?

Paula Parrot starts on a number line at 0 and wants to reach 2. She can hop only $\frac{1}{4}$ of the distance to her goal in each hop. Each subsequent hop is $\frac{1}{4}$ of the remaining distance to the goal. How far has she hopped after four hops? Express your answer as a common fraction.

Peter has a deck of  $1001$  cards, and with a blue pen he has written the numbers  $1,2,\ldots,1001$  on the cards (one number on each card). He replaced cards in a circle so that blue numbers were on the bottom side of the card. Then, for each card  $C$ , he took  $500$  consecutive cards following  $C$  (clockwise order), and denoted by  $f(C)$  the number of blue numbers written on those  $500$  cards that are greater than the blue number written on  $C$  itself. After all, he wrote this  $f(C)$  number on the top side of the card  $C$  with a red pen. Prove that Peter's friend Basil, who sees all the red numbers on these cards, can determine the blue number on each card.

Petya and Vasya ride bicycles at constant speeds around a circle. Petya's speed is 8 km/h, and Vasya's speed is 10 km/h. Initially, they rode in opposite directions (Petya clockwise and Vasya counterclockwise), and then Petya changed his direction (started moving counterclockwise) and simultaneously doubled his speed. After this, the cyclists met $k$ times less frequently. Find $k$.
Point $A$ on the number line represents $-2$. Starting from point $A$, moving $4$ units along the number line will reach point $B$. The number represented by point $B$ is ____.
Point $D$ is on side $AC$ of triangle $ABC$, where $\angle ABD=20^\circ$ and $\angle DBC=30^\circ$. If $\angle C=120^\circ$, what is the measure of $\angle BAD$?

Point $P(-2,-3)$ is moved $1$ unit to the left and then $3$ units up. The coordinates of the resulting point are:

A: $(-3,0)$

B: $(-1,6)$

C: $(-3,-6)$

D: $(-1,0)$
Point \( O \) is the center of the circle. What is the value of angle \( x \) in degrees?

Points $A,B,C,D,E$ and $F$ lie, in that order, on $\overline{AF}$, dividing it into five segments, each of length 1. Point $G$ is not on line $AF$. Point $H$ lies on $\overline{GD}$, and point $J$ lies on $\overline{GF}$. The line segments $\overline{HC}, \overline{JE},$ and $\overline{AG}$ are parallel. Find $HC/JE$.
$\text{(A)}\ 5/4 \qquad \text{(B)}\ 4/3 \qquad \text{(C)}\ 3/2 \qquad \text{(D)}\ 5/3 \qquad \text{(E)}\ 2$
Positive numbers \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\) satisfy the condition \(c^{2} + ab = a^{2} + b^{2}\). Prove the inequality \(c^{2} + ab \leq ac + bc\).

Problem 3.
Let  $f:\left[ 0,\frac{\pi }{2} \right]\to \left[ 0,\infty  \right)$   an increasing function .Prove that:
(a)  $\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi }{2}}{\left( f\left( x \right)-f\left( \frac{\pi }{4} \right) \right)}\left( \sin x-\cos x \right)dx\ge 0.$ (b) Exist  $a\in \left[ \frac{\pi }{4},\frac{\pi }{2} \right]$   such that  $\int_{0}^{a}{f\left( x \right)\sin x\ dx=}\int_{0}^{a}{f\left( x \right)\cos x\ dx}.$

Prove that

$$
\int_{0}^{\pi}|\ln \sin x| \, dx \leq \frac{\pi^{3}}{12}
$$

where $\ln$ denotes the natural logarithm with base $e = 2.71\ldots$.

Prove that a circle and a tangent line to it, upon inversion, transform into either two tangent circles, a circle and a tangent line, or a pair of parallel lines.

Definition: Let two circles intersect at point \( A \). The angle between the circles is defined as the angle between the tangents to the circles at point \( A \). (Clearly, if the circles intersect at points \( A \) and \( B \), then the angle between the tangents at point \( A \) is equal to the angle between the tangents at point \( B \).) The angle between a line and a circle is defined similarly.
Prove that a polynomial \( P(z) \) is an even function of \( z \in \mathbb{C} \) if and only if there exists a polynomial \( Q(z) \) such that \( P(z) \equiv Q(z) Q(-z) \) for \( z \in \mathbb{C} \).

Prove that for \( n \geqslant 1 \) and \( m \geqslant 0 \) the following equality holds:
\[ 
F_{n+m} = F_{n-1} F_{m} + F_{n} F_{m+1} 
\]

Try to prove it in two ways: using the method of mathematical induction and using the Fibonacci number interpretation from problem 3.109. Also, prove that Cassini's identity (see problem 3.112) is a special case of this equality.

Prove that for any natural number \( n \):

$$
\frac{1^{2}}{1 \cdot 3}+\frac{2^{2}}{3 \cdot 5}+\ldots+\frac{n^{2}}{(2 n-1)(2 n+1)}=\frac{n(n+1)}{2(2 n+1)}
$$

Prove that for any positive integer \( n \), the following inequality holds:
\[ \lg n \geqslant k \lg 2 \]
where \( k \) is the number of distinct prime factors of \( n \).
Prove that if \( P Q \| A C \), then triangle \( A B C \) is isosceles.
Prove that if a positive integer \(k\) is divisible by 10101010 101, then at least 6 digits in its decimal representation are non-zero.
Prove that in a right-angled triangle, the distance between the incenter and the circumcenter is at least $(\sqrt{2}-1)$ times the radius of the circumcircle.
Prove that it is possible to write a non-negative number on each edge of an arbitrary tetrahedron such that the sum of the numbers on the edges of each face is equal to the area of that face.
Prove that the altitude drawn from the vertex of the right angle in a scalene right triangle is less than half of the hypotenuse.

Prove that the solution set of the inequality $\sum_{k=1}^{10} \frac{k}{x-k} \geqslant \frac{5}{4}$ is the intersection of non-overlapping intervals, and that the sum of the lengths of these intervals is 1988.
Prove that the square of an odd number, when divided by 8, leaves a remainder of 1.

Read the following material:
There is a close relationship between exponentials and logarithms, and they can be interconverted.
Definition of logarithm: Generally, if $a^{x}=N(a \gt 0$ and $a eq 1)$, then $x$ is called the logarithm of $N$ with base $a$, denoted as $x=\log _{a}N$. For example, the exponential expression $2^{4}=16$ can be converted into the logarithmic expression $4=\log _{2}16$, and the logarithmic expression $2=\log _{5}25$ can be converted into the exponential expression $5^{2}=25$. According to the definition of logarithm, we can obtain a property of logarithms:
$\log _{a}(M\cdot N)=\log _{a}M+\log _{a}N\left(a \gt 0,a eq 1,M \gt 0,N \gt 0 ight)$, the reason is as follows:
Let $\log _{a}M=m$ and $\log _{a}N=n$, then $M=a^{m}$ and $N=a^{n}$,
$ herefore M\cdot N=a^{m}\cdot a^{n}=a^{m+n}$, according to the definition of logarithm, we have $m+n=\log _{a}(M\cdot N)$
Also, since $m+n=\log _{a}M+\log _{a}N$,
Therefore, $\log _{a}(M\cdot N)=\log _{a}M+\log _{a}N$. Please solve the following problems:
$(1)$ Convert the exponential expression $3^{4}=81$ into a logarithmic expression ______;
$(2)$ Prove that $\log _{a} rac{M}{N}=\log _{a}M-\log _{a}N\left(a \gt 0,a eq 1,M \gt 0,N \gt 0 ight)$;
$(3)$ Extended application: Calculate $\log _{6}9+\log _{6}8-\log _{6}2=\_\_\_\_\_\_$.

We know that the expansion of $(a+b)^{2}$ is $a^{2}+2ab+b^{2}$. We can use the polynomial multiplication rule to expand $(a+b)^{3}$. If we go further and want to expand $(a+b)^{4}$, $(a+b)^{5}$, you will definitely find that solving the above problems requires a lot of calculations. Is there a simpler method? Let's look for a pattern!

If we arrange each term of $(a+b)^{n}$ (where n is a non-negative integer) in descending order according to the number of times the letter $a$ appears, we can get the following equation:

Number of terms in the calculation result and coefficients of each term:

$(a+b)^{0}=1\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 1\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 1$

$(a+b)^{1}=a+b\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 2\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 1\ \ \ 1$

$(a+b)^{2}=a^{2}+2ab+b^{2}\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 3\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 1\ \ \ \ 2\ \ \ \ 1$

$(a+b)^{3}=a^{3}+3a^{2}b+3ab^{2}+b^{3}\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 4\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ 1\ \ \ \ 3\ \ \ \ 3\ \ \ \ 1$

The sequence  $a_1 = 1$ ,  $a_2, a_3, \cdots$   is defined as follows: if  $a_n - 2$  is a natural number not already occurring on the board, then  $a_{n+1} = a_n-2$ ; otherwise,  $a_{n+1} = a_n + 3$ .  Prove that every nonzero perfect square occurs in the sequence as the previous term increased by  $3$ .

The sequence $\left\{a_{n}\right\}$ is defined as follows: $a_{1}=\frac{1}{2}$, and $a_{n+1}=\frac{a_{n}^{2}}{a_{n}^{2}-a_{n}+1}$ for $n=1,2,\ldots$. Prove that for every positive integer $n$, the inequality $a_{1}+a_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}<1$ holds.

The sequence $\{a_n\}$ has a sum of the first $n$ terms $S_n$ satisfying $S_n= \frac {3}{2}a_n- \frac {1}{2}a_1$, and $a_1$, $a_2+6$, $a_3$ form an arithmetic sequence.  
(I) Find the general formula for the sequence $\{a_n\}$.  
(II) Let $b_n= \frac {a_{n+1}}{S_nS_{n+1}}$, find the sum of the first $n$ terms of the sequence $\{b_n\}$, $T_n$.

The sequence of digits
\[
1 2 3 4 5 6 7 8 9 1 0 1 1 1 2 1 3 1 4 1 5 1 6 1 7 1 8 1 9 2 0 2 1 \dots
\]
is obtained by writing the positive integers in order. If the  $10^n$ -th digit in this sequence occurs in the part of the sequence in which the  $m$ -digit numbers are placed, define  $f(n)$  to be  $m$ . For example,  $f(2)=2$  because the 100th digit enters the sequence in the placement of the two-digit integer 55. Find, with proof,  $f(1987)$ .
The side of a square is increased by some percentage, and its area increases by 56.25%. By what percentage was the side of the square increased?
The sidewalk in front of Lila's house is 15 feet long and 3 feet wide. If the snow is 0.6 feet deep, how many cubic feet of snow does Lila have to shovel off the sidewalk?

The slant height of a cone is 10, and its height is 8. Then, the surface area of this cone is (　　)
A: 60π
B: 80π
C: 96π
D: 116π

The slope of the line $x+\sqrt{3}y+2=0$ is ( ).

A: $\frac{{5π}}{6}$

B: $\frac{{2π}}}{3}$

C: $\frac{π}{3}$

D: $\frac{π}{6}$

The slope of the tangent line to $f(x) = x^3 + x^2 + 1$ at $x = 1$ is ( )
A: 2
B: 3
C: 4
D: 5
The solution set of the inequality $2x^2 - 3x - 2 > 0$ is ______.
The solution set of the inequality $x^2 + 2x < 3$ is expressed as ______. (The answer should be expressed in the form of a set)

The space is partitioned by the set of planes
$$
A=\{x \pm y \pm z=n, n \in \mathbf{Z}\}
$$

into some combination of tetrahedra and octahedra. Suppose a rational point $\left(x_{0}, y_{0}, z_{0}\right)$ does not belong to any plane in $A$. Prove that there exists a positive integer $k$ such that the point $\left(k x_{0}, k y_{0}, k z_{0}\right)$ is located inside some octahedron formed by the planes in $A$.

The square  $ABCD$  is inscribed in a circle with center  $O$ . Let  $E$  be the midpoint of  $AD$ . The line  $CE$  meets the circle again at  $F$ . The lines  $FB$  and  $AD$  meet at  $H$ . Prove  $HD = 2AH$

The stem-and-leaf plot below shows the duration of rides (in minutes and seconds) on each of the 20 top-rated roller coasters in two categories: Category A (shorter rides) and Category B (longer rides). Interpret these times in seconds and calculate the median ride duration for each category.

Category A:
\begin{tabular}{c|cccc}
0&25&30&45&50\\
1&05&10&15&40\\
2&05&15&20&30\\
\end{tabular}

Category B:
\begin{tabular}{c|ccc}
1&55&58&60\\
2&02&15&30\\
3&20&25&48\\
4&10&15&\\
\end{tabular}
The sum of all eight numbers \(a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_8\) is \(\frac{4}{3}\), and the sum of any seven of them is positive. Find all possible values that the smallest of these numbers can take.
The sum of five numbers is three-quarters. What is the mean of these five numbers? Express your answer as a common fraction.
The sum of the first three terms of a geometric sequence $\{a_n\}$ is equal to three times its first term. Then, the common ratio of this geometric sequence is __________.
The sum of the lengths of the four sides of a rhombus is 32. What is the length of one side?
The sum of the present age of Henry and Jill is 48. Their present ages are such that 9 years ago, Henry was twice the age of Jill. What is Henry's present age?
The sum of three numbers $a$, $b$, and $c$ is 120. If we increase $a$ by 8, decrease $b$ by 3 and multiply $c$ by 3, the three resulting numbers are equal. What is the value of $b$?

The sum of three numbers is $120$. The ratio of the first to the second is $\frac{3}{4}$, and the ratio of the second to the third is $\frac{4}{7}$. Find the second number.
A) $\frac{210}{7}$
B) $\frac{220}{7}$
C) $\frac{230}{7}$
D) $\frac{240}{7}$
E) $\frac{250}{7}$

The sum of two nonzero real numbers is $3$ times their product. What is the sum of the reciprocals of the two numbers?
A) 1  
B) 2  
C) 3  
D) 4  
E) 6

The system of inequalities $$\begin{cases} \overset{x>a}{y>b}\end{cases}$$ is the ( ) of the system of inequalities $$\begin{cases} \overset{x+y>a+b}{xy>ab}\end{cases}$$
A: Sufficient but not necessary condition
B: Necessary but not sufficient condition
C: Necessary and sufficient condition
D: Neither necessary nor sufficient condition

The total corn yield in centners, harvested from a certain field area, is expressed as a four-digit number composed of the digits 0, 2, 3, and 5. When the average yield per hectare was calculated, it was found to be the same number of centners as the number of hectares of the field area. Determine the total corn yield.
The town of Milburg has 5256 grown-ups and children. 2987 are children. How many adults live in Milburg?

The universal set is the set of real numbers \\(R\\), \\(M=\\{x|-2\leqslant x\leqslant 2\\}\\), \\(N=\\{x|x < 1\\}\\), then \\((\complement_{R}M)\cap N=\\)　　\\()
A: \\(\\{x|x < -2\\}\\)
B: \\(\\{x|-2 < x < 1\\}\\)
C: \\(\\{x|x < 1\\}\\)
D: \\(\\{x|-2\leqslant x < 1\\}\\)

The value of $\sin 210^\circ$ is equal to (　　)

A: $-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$
B: $\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}$
C: $-\frac{1}{2}$
D: $\frac{1}{2}$

The vectors $\mathbf{a},$ $\mathbf{b},$ and $\mathbf{c}$ satisfy $\|\mathbf{a}\| = \|\mathbf{b}\| = 1,$ $\|\mathbf{c}\| = 3,$ and are arranged so that $\mathbf{a} \times (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{c}) + \mathbf{b} = \mathbf{0}$. Additionally, it's given that $\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c} = 0$. If $\theta$ is the angle between $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{c}$, then find all possible values of $\theta$ in degrees.

The zero of the function $f(x) = 1 - \log_{2}x$ is (　　)  
A: $(1, 1)$  
B: $1$  
C: $(2, 0)$  
D: $2$

There are  $24$  participants attended a meeting. Each two of them shook hands once or not. A total of  $216$  handshakes occured in the meeting. For any two participants who have shaken hands, at most  $10$  among the rest  $22$  participants have shaken hands with exactly one of these two persons. Define a *friend circle* to be a group of  $3$  participants in which each person has shaken hands with the other two. Find the minimum possible value of friend circles.

There are $2^n$ balls divided into several piles. We can choose any two piles, denoted as pile A and pile B, and move balls according to the following rule: if the number of balls in pile A, denoted as $p$, is no less than the number of balls in pile B, denoted as $q$, then move $q$ balls from pile A to pile B. This counts as one move. Prove that it is possible to combine all the balls into one pile through a finite number of moves.
There are $n (>1)$ points on a circle, labeled as $p_{1}, p_{2}, \cdots, p_{n}$. Determine the number of ways to connect these points with a non-self-intersecting polyline $p_{1} p_{2} \cdots p_{n}$.
There are 10 balls. Jungkook wants to put 5 balls in one box. How many boxes does he need at this time?

There are 12 different cards, including 3 red, 3 yellow, 3 blue, and 3 green cards. If 3 cards are drawn at random, the requirement is that these 3 cards cannot all be of the same color, and at most 1 of the cards can be red. The number of different ways to draw the cards is \_\_\_\_\_\_.
There are 2 pencils in the drawer. Tim placed some pencils in the drawer. There are now 5 pencils in total. How many pencils did Tim place in the drawer?

There are 2 sections, A and B, in a class, consisting of 50 and 40 students respectively. The average weight of section A is 50 kg, and that of section B is a certain value. The average weight of the whole class is 58.89 kg. What is the average weight of section B?
There are 20 parts in total, among which 16 are good and 4 are defective. If we randomly pick 3 parts from these 20, find the number of different ways in which at least one good part is included.

There are 30 people in a club. 12 of them are left-handed. 20 of them like jazz music. 3 of them are right-handed and dislike jazz music. How many club members are left-handed and like jazz music? Assume people are either left-handed or right-handed, but not both.

There are 40 externally identical coins, among which 3 are counterfeit and they weigh the same and are lighter than the real ones (the real coins also weigh the same). How can you use three weighings on a balance scale without weights to select 16 real coins?

There are 42 apples in a crate. 12 crates of apples were delivered to a factory. Some apples were rotten and had to be thrown away. The remaining apples were packed into boxes that could fit 10 apples each. There were 50 boxes of apples. How many apples were rotten and had to be thrown away?

There are 45 students in a certain exam in the Zhonghuan Cup. Among them, 35 students are good at English, 31 students are good at Chinese, and 24 students are good at both subjects. How many students are not good at either subject?

There are 8 different positive integers. Among them, at least 6 are multiples of 2, at least 5 are multiples of 3, at least 3 are multiples of 5, and at least 1 is a multiple of 7. To minimize the largest number among these 8 integers, what is this largest number?

There are \( n \) cars waiting at distinct points of a circular race track. At the starting signal, each car starts. Each car may choose arbitrarily which of the two possible directions to go. Each car has the same constant speed. Whenever two cars meet, they both change direction (but not speed). Show that, at some time, each car is back at its starting point.

There are a total of $400$ machine parts. If person A works alone for $1$ day, and then person A and person B work together for $2$ days, there will still be $60$ parts unfinished. If both work together for $3$ days, they can produce $20$ parts more than needed. How many parts can each person make per day?

There are five monkeys and five ladders. At the top of each ladder, there is a banana. The ladders are connected by ropes, with each rope connecting two rungs on different ladders. No rung has more than one rope attached to it. Initially, each monkey is at the bottom of a different ladder, and they climb up the ladders, changing their paths whenever they encounter a rope, and continue climbing after reaching the other end of the rope. Prove that, no matter how many ropes there are, each monkey will eventually get to one banana.
There are some ducks in a pond. 50 percent of the ducks are Muscovy and 30 percent of the Muscovies are female. There are 6 female Muscovy ducks. How many ducks are there in the pond?

There are three numbers in arithmetic progression. The triple of the sum of the first two numbers is exactly twice the third number. If the second number is reduced by 2, then the resulting number is the geometric mean of the first and third numbers. Find the original three numbers.

There are two circles of different radii. The area of a square is 784 sq cm and its side is twice the radius of the larger circle. The radius of the larger circle is related to that of the smaller circle. The circumference of the smaller circle is 8. What is the ratio of the radius of the larger circle to the radius of the smaller circle?

There are two piles, each containing 100 matches. Two players engage in a game where the first player discards one of the two piles and splits the other pile into two (possibly unequal) piles. Then the second player performs the same operation, and so on. Can the first player guarantee a win if the loser is the player who cannot split a pile into two parts? If so, how should the first player play?
There are two wallets and one coin. Inside the first wallet, there is one coin, and inside the second wallet, there is one coin. How can this be?

There is 80 mg of caffeine in a cup of coffee. Lisa does not want to drink more than 200 mg of caffeine per day. She drinks a certain number of cups of coffee and ends up drinking 40 milligrams of coffee over her goal. How many cups of coffee did Lisa drink?

There is a 10x10 grid for a game of "Battleship." In this case, the game is played by unusual rules, and you are only allowed to use ships of size 1x2 which can be placed either horizontally or vertically. What is the maximum number of these ships that can be placed on the grid if the ships must not come into contact with each other, even at a single point?

There is a cage with 10 cats, including 7 white cats and 3 black cats. The cage door is opened slightly, allowing only one cat to exit at a time. The cats rush out one by one. If all 10 cats exit the cage, let \( X \) represent the number of segments into which the 7 white cats are divided by the 3 black cats. For example, in a certain exit sequence, \( X \) can be 3 because the 7 white cats are divided into 3 segments. Find the distribution of \( X \).

There is a poem: "There is a student of good nature, who finished reading 'Mencius' in three days. Each day, he reads more than double the amount of the previous day. How much does he read each day?" (Note: The book 'Mencius' has a total of 34685 characters, "more than double" refers to double the amount.) From this poem, we know the number of characters he read on the first day is ▲.

There is a special calculator. When a number is input, the calculator will multiply the number by 2, then reverse the digits of the result. Finally, it will add 2 and display the final result. If you input a two-digit number and the final displayed result is 27, what was the initial input?

There were 18 students assigned in a minibus for a field trip. Some of these students were boys. On the day of the field trip, the number of girls and boys was the same since some of the girls were not able to join the trip. Two girls were not able to join the field trip. How many boys were assigned in the minibus for the field trip?

There were 21 roses in the vase. Jessica threw away 34 roses from the vase and cut some more new roses from her flower garden to put in the vase. There are now 15 roses in the vase.. How many more roses did she throw away than those she cut from her garden?
There were a total of 12 football games this year. Melanie missed 7 of the games. In all, Melanie went to _____ football games.

Thirty-six players are playing a game: they take turns drawing a random card from a 36-card deck. If a player draws the ace of diamonds, they win. If they draw any other card, they return it to the deck, and the next player takes their turn. This continues in a cycle: first player, then the second, and so on. If the ace of diamonds is not drawn in the first round, the players continue drawing cards in the same order in the second round, and so on. This process repeats until someone draws the ace of diamonds.

Assume that before the game starts, the players place bets, and the winner takes all. How should the players' bets be related so that the game is fair, meaning the expected winnings for all players are equal to each other (i.e., equal to zero taking into account the amount each player bet)?

Three cards are dealt sequentially from a standard deck of 52 cards. What is the probability that the first card is a club $\clubsuit$, the second card is a diamond $\diamondsuit$, and the third card is a heart $\heartsuit$?

Three complex numbers form three of the vertices of a square in the complex plane: $2 + 3i, -1 + 4i$, and $-3 - 2i$. Find the coordinates of the fourth vertex.
A) $-4 - 5i$
B) $-4 + 5i$
C) $4 - 5i$
D) $4 + 5i$
E) $-5 - 4i$

Three cones with vertex \(A\) touch each other externally, with the first two having an apex angle of \(\frac{\pi}{6}\). Each of the cones touches internally a fourth cone with a vertex at point \(A\) and an apex angle of \(\frac{\pi}{3}\). Find the apex angle of the third cone. (The apex angle of a cone is defined as the angle between its generatrices in the axial section.)

Three friends, each with some money, redistribute the money as follows:
Amy triples Jan's amount and doubles Toy's amount.
Jan then doubles Amy's and triples Toy's amounts.
Finally, Toy gives enough to Amy and Jan to triple their amounts.
If Toy had 24 dollars at the beginning and 24 dollars at the end, what is the total amount that all three friends have?
**A**. 48
**B**. 72
**C**. 96
**D**. 108
Three of the roots of the equation \[ax^4 + bx^3 + cx^2 + dx + e = 0\] are $5$, $-3$, and $1$. Given that $a \neq 0$, compute $\frac{b+c+d}{a}$.
Three positive integers have a sum of 90 and are in the ratio 1:3:5. What is the least of these three integers?
Through a point \( P \) three segments parallel to the sides of triangle \( ABC \) are drawn (see figure). Prove that the areas of triangles \( A_{1}B_{1}C_{1} \) and \( A_{2}B_{2}C_{2} \) are equal.

Tim is 5 years old. His cousin, Rommel, is a certain multiple of Tim's age. His other cousin, Jenny, is 2 years older than Rommel. Tim is 12 years younger than Jenny. What is the ratio of Rommel's age to Tim's age?

To $p$ ounces of a $p\%$ solution of acid, $y$ ounces of water are added to yield a $(\frac{2p}{3})\%$ solution. Assuming $p > 45$, find the value of $y$.
A) $\frac{p}{2}$
B) $\frac{2p}{3}$
C) $\frac{p}{3}$
D) $\frac{p}{4}$
E) $\frac{3p}{4}$

To obtain the graph of the function $f(x) = 2^{1-x}$, one can ( )
A: Shift the graph of the function $y = 2^x$ to the left by 1 unit
B: Shift the graph of the function $y = 2^x$ horizontally by 1 unit
C: Shift the graph of the function $y = 2^{-x}$ to the left by 1 unit
D: Shift the graph of the function $y = 2^{-x}$ to the right by 1 unit

To obtain the graph of the function $y=4\cos 2x$, all you need to do is move each point $( \ \ )$ on the graph of the function $y=4\cos (2x+ \frac {π}{4})$:
A: horizontally to the left by $\frac {π}{4}$ units
B: horizontally to the right by $\frac {π}{4}$ units
C: horizontally to the left by $\frac {π}{8}$ units
D: horizontally to the right by $\frac {π}{8}$ units

To paint a cube on all sides requires 60 grams of paint. How much paint will be needed to paint a "snake" formed by 2016 such cubes? The beginning and end of the snake are shown in the illustration, and the remaining cubes are replaced by ellipses.

To prove the proposition "In $\triangle ABC$, if $\angle A \neq \angle B$, then $AC \neq BC$" using proof by contradiction, one should first assume that

A: $AC > BC$

B: $AC < BC$

C: $\angle A = \angle B$

D: $AC = BC$

Tom drives from town A to town B, driving at a constant speed of 60 miles per hour. From town B, Tom immediately continues to town C at a speed of 20 miles per hour. The distance between A and B is twice the distance between B and C. What is the average speed of the whole journey in miles per hour?

Tom opened a shop investing Rs. 30,000. Jose joined him 2 months later, investing Rs. 45,000. Four months after Tom started the business, Maria also joined them, investing Rs. 60,000. Over the course of a year, each month's profit or loss varied. The monthly net amounts were as follows:

1. Rs. 5,000 profit
2. Rs. 2,000 loss
3. Rs. 7,000 profit
4. Rs. 1,000 profit
5. Rs. 3,000 loss
6. Rs. 10,000 profit
7. Rs. 500 profit
8. Rs. 4,000 profit
9. Rs. 2,500 loss
10. Rs. 6,000 profit
11. Rs. 8,000 profit
12. Rs. 1,000 loss

With these varying profits and losses, what will be Jose's share of the overall profit at the end of the year?
Tommy wants to earn enough money to buy 8 new books. Each book costs $5. Tommy already has some money and he needs to save up $27. How much money does Tommy already have?

Translate the curve \( y \cos x + 2y - 1 = 0 \) first by \(\frac{\pi}{2}\) units to the right along the \(x\)-axis, and then by 1 unit downward along the \(y\)-axis. The equation of the resulting curve is:

A. \((1 - y) \sin x + 2y - 3 = 0\)
B. \((y - 1) \sin x + 2y - 3 = 0\)
C. \((y + 1) \sin x + 2y + 1 = 0\)
D. \(-(y + 1) \sin x + 2y + 1 = 0\)
Triangles $PAQ$ and $PQC$ are right triangles in quadrilateral $PACQ$ with $AP = 10$ units, $PQ = 24$ units, and $PC = 26$ units. Calculate the area, in square units, of quadrilateral $PACQ$.

Triangles \( ABC \) and \( A_{1}B_{1}C_{1} \) have parallel sides, with sides \( AB \) and \( A_{1}B_{1} \) lying on the same line. Prove that the line connecting the points of intersection of the circumscribed circles of triangles \( A_{1}BC \) and \( AB_{1}C \) contains point \( C_{1} \).
Two 8-sided dice are tossed. What is the probability that the sum of the numbers shown on the dice is a prime number? Express your answer as a common fraction.

Two boys, Ben and Leo, are fond of playing marbles. Ben has 56 marbles, while Leo has a certain number of marbles more than Ben. They put the marbles in one jar. There are 132 marbles in the jar. How many more marbles does Leo have than Ben?

Two circles $(x-2)^2+(y+3)^2=13$ and $(x-3)^2+y^2=9$ intersect at points A and B. Find the equation of the perpendicular bisector of segment AB.

A: $x+y+3=0$

B: $2x-y-5=0$

C: $3x-y-9=0$

D: $4x-3y+7=0$

Two congruent 30-60-90 triangles are placed such that one triangle is translated 2 units vertically upwards, while their hypotenuses originally coincide when not translated. The hypotenuse of each triangle is 10. Calculate the area common to both triangles when one is translated.
A. \(15\sqrt{3} - 5\)
B. \(25\sqrt{3} - 10\)
C. \(35\sqrt{3} - 5\)
D. \(45\sqrt{3} - 15\)

Two congruent 30-60-90 triangles are placed such that their hypotenuses coincide fully, and one triangle is rotated 30° around the midpoint of the hypotenuse relative to the other. If the hypotenuse of each triangle is 24, find the area common to both triangles.
A. $72$
B. $108$
C. $216$
D. $432$
E. $864$

Two drones start at the same point and fly at the same rate. Drone $A$ travels $1$ foot northeast, then $1$ foot southeast, then $1$ foot upwards, and repeats this pattern. Drone $B$ travels $1$ foot southwest, then $1$ foot northwest, then $1$ foot upwards, and repeats this pattern. Determine the directions the drones are traveling when they are exactly $12$ feet away from each other.
A) A northeast, B southwest
B) A southeast, B northwest
C) A upwards, B upwards
D) A northeast, B northwest

Two fill taps A and B can separately fill a cistern in 45 and 40 minutes respectively. They started to fill a cistern together but tap A is turned off after 9 minutes. How many minutes does it take for tap B to fill the rest part of the cistern?
Two fruits were taken out from a basket containing one apple, one peach, one pear, one melon, and a strawberry. How many ways are there for the selected fruit?
Two identical circles with radii of $1256 \mathrm{~m}$ intersect in such a way that their centers are $50 \mathrm{~m}$ apart. Calculate the area common to both circles.

Two jars are filled with alcohol solutions, the first having a total volume \( V \) and a ratio of the volume of alcohol to water of \( p:2 \), and the second jar having a total volume \( 2V \) and a ratio \( q:1 \). If the contents of the two jars are mixed together, what is the ratio of the volume of alcohol to the volume of water in the mixture?
A) \(\frac{p+4q}{6}\)
B) \(\frac{q+4p}{6}\)
C) \(\frac{p(q+1)+4q(p+2)}{2(q+1)+4(p+2)}\)
D) \(\frac{p+q}{3}\)
E) \(\frac{5pq}{2p+3q}\)

Two pipes A and B can fill a tank in 10 hours and some hours respectively. If both the pipes are opened simultaneously, the tank will be filled in approximately 6 hours. How much time will pipe B take to fill the tank alone?

Two pipes can fill a tank in 18 minutes and some minutes. An outlet pipe can empty the tank in 45 minutes. If all the pipes are opened when the tank is empty, it will take 0.08333333333333333 minutes to fill the tank. How many minutes does it take for the second pipe to fill the tank?

Two trains are moving in opposite directions with speeds of 315 km/hr and 135 km/hr respectively. Their lengths are 1.65 km and 1.35 km respectively. The slower train crosses the faster train in - - - seconds.

Two trains of equal length are running on parallel lines in the same direction at some speed and 36 km/hr. The faster train passes the slower train in 36 seconds. The length of each train is 65 meters. What is the speed of the faster train?

Two trains of equal length are running on parallel lines in the same direction. One train is running at 42 km/hr, and the other train is running at a certain speed. The faster train passes the slower train in 36 seconds. The length of each train is 30 meters. What is the speed of the slower train?

Two wheels are spun. The first wheel has 5 sections with 2 being even numbers and the second wheel has 4 sections with 2 being even numbers. Calculate the probability that the sum of the numbers obtained from spinning both wheels is even.
A. $\frac{1}{3}$  
B. $\frac{1}{2}$  
C. $\frac{3}{5}$  
D. $\frac{2}{3}$  
E. $\frac{3}{4}$

Two years ago, Mr. Ma bought a mobile phone. Now, the price of this mobile phone has dropped to 1000 yuan. Assuming the price of this type of mobile phone decreases by 20% every year, the price of the mobile phone two years ago was (　　)
A: 1535.5 yuan
B: 1440 yuan
C: 1620 yuan
D: 1562.5 yuan

Use a rectangular iron sheet measuring 90cm in length and 48cm in width to make an open-top rectangular container. First, cut out a small square at each of the four corners. Then, fold the four sides up at a 90-degree angle and weld them together. When the side length of the cut-out square is ______ cm, the volume of the rectangular container is maximized.
Use the Horner's method to calculate the value of the polynomial $f(x) = 7x^5 + 12x^4 - 5x^3 - 6x^2 + 3x - 5$ at $x = 7$.
Use the method of successive subtraction to find the greatest common divisor of 459 and 357.

Using the digits $0$, $1$, $2$, $3$, $4$, $5$, how many different five-digit even numbers greater than $20000$ can be formed without repeating any digit?
A: $288$
B: $240$
C: $144$
D: $126$
Using the digits 1, 2, 3, 4, how many distinct four-digit even numbers can be formed?
Vanya thought of a two-digit number, then swapped its digits and multiplied the resulting number by itself. The result was four times the original number. What number did Vanya think of?

Vasya can make the number 100 using ten threes, parentheses, and arithmetic operations: $100=(33: 3-3: 3) \cdot(33: 3-3: 3)$. Improve his result: use fewer threes to obtain the number 100. (One example is enough).

Wanda the Worm likes to eat Pascal's triangle. One day, she starts at the top of the triangle and eats $\binom{0}{0}=1$. Each move, she travels to an adjacent positive integer and eats it, but she can never return to a spot that she has previously eaten. If Wanda can never eat numbers \( a, b, \) and \( c \) such that \( a + b = c \), prove that it is possible for her to eat 100,000 numbers in the first 2011 rows given that she is not restricted to traveling only in the first 2011 rows.

(Here, the \( n+1 \)-st row of Pascal's triangle consists of entries of the form \( \binom{n}{k} \) for integers \( 0 \leq k \leq n \).
